caption: What a great restaurant. The interior is great and it has an outside lounge and eating area that is amazing. We started off with the mussels. They were unbelievable.  The white wine sauce was tasty. For dinner I had the skirt steak. It was delicious.  The cocktails I had were great. The service was great. Brandon was informative and attentive.
I really did enjoy the food here and their service staff were great too. Looking forward to next time trying more items on their menu.

Had so much fun with my girls here the other night! We sat in the super cozy, smaller outdoor cafe, and tucked ourselves away into a far, quiet corner. We laughed, drank, and stuffed ourselves with INCREDIBLE salads--the burrata salad and the kale salad with chicken are a must try! My friend who is on a new keto diet ordered the burger without the bun--she kept exclaiming how huge, juicy and delicious it was! All of this mixed with kind, attentive service made our night super special!  For a few short fleeting moments, it felt like life before March 2020, and we almost forgot that we were in the middle of a pandemic. These days (always!) we all deserve and need moments of happiness like we got to experience last night in this lovely, magical establishment.

Honestly, the food was not great. At all. I was torn between 3 and 4 stars because the outdoor space is really, really beautiful and the service was excellent.... But every single item of food we had was definitely below average and I wouldn't be excited to eat, let alone buy any of it again. For reference, we ordered some cold cuts & cheese, all of which were lower in quality than what we'd get at our local supermarket, two pastas - the meat parpadelle wasn't bad but my shrimp pasta tasted like it had sweet chilli sauce or something far too sweet cooked in, and giant chunks of onion... Very disappointing. Then the wine tasted pretty cheap, a lot lower quality than it should have been for $11/glass.

They have live music in the back room 4 nights during the week which is amazing. We went on a Wednesday evening and it was a great jazz/ soul ensemble.  They have two different patios which is really cool, for whatever social mood you're in. Honestly, can't recommend this place enough. The owners Paul and Chris are incredibly friendly and professional, they really take pride in the restaurant and venue. Beyond excited to bring more friends around.

I resigned myself to a cozy evening inside, when the sun came out and my girlfriend called to invite me out for dinner. We came here because it's one of her favorite spots in the neighborhood, and she couldn't believe that I had never come before. We sat outside in the beautiful, plant filled cafe and soaked in the beautiful evening, and scenery! There are so many cool knicknacks to look at among the plants and flowers, and a cool assortment of people also enjoying dinner and drinks. We shared a bottle of the special white wine that the server told us about, and switched plates midway through our dinner, so we could both enjoy the handmade pasta(meat lasagna that was PERFECT) and the red snapper(lightly seasoned and perfectly cooked). As if my impromptu night out couldn't get any better, our server mentioned that there was live music about to start in the back lounge area. We took our glasses of wine and settled into a cozy couch to watch some of the best live jazz and R&B that I've seen in awhile. Over all, I'm SO glad I didn't stay in the other night, and can't wait to be back to my new favorite neighborhood spot.

We stopped by just for cocktails and had a decidedly upsetting experience. Let me preface that this review is really about a particular bartender who worked here that evening (6/23/2018), and not the establishment itself. Me and my girlfriend ordered two cocktails, the Mezcal Old Fashioned for me (which tasted perfectly fine), and The Escobar for her. We both thought her drink tasted awful, like beyond awful. It tasted honestly like it had been mixed with some vomit in it. I just had a taste of it and I have flashbacks to how awful the taste was in my mouth even the next day. I'm looking back at their menu and maybe their mango puree somehow went bad...? But it was TERRIBLE. I went back up to ask for another drink. I asked for the Ginger Caipirinha, thinking it was a safe bet. Bartender didn't look too pleased, but obliged. The drink came back kind of thick and viscous, with some thick bubbles in it (you can use your imagination here) which made me really suspicious, since I chose the Capirinha because it is usually made with only clear liquids and no purees. That drink tasted really, really bad too, like intentionally bad... I've been thinking about just how upsetting this whole experience was and how that bartender seriously may have been spiking drinks with God knows what in those squeeze bottles. It really put a damper on our whole evening, and was one of the more upsetting experiences I've had in a while. If I were the owner I would start asking questions ... it's a shame because the establishment itself looked like a really great place that I would have revisited.

Stopped in for a bite to eat before a show at Brooklyn Steel last night. We were seated quickly. We ordered drinks and our meal shortly after. The recommended wine special was very good. But, my husband's cocktail had about 2 and a half sips in there. The glass was full of ice. Oh well. We had the grilled zucchin with goat cheese and mesculin greens as a shared appetizer. The zucchini was barely grilled, practically raw and when you cut into it the greens were everywhere. And the greens weren't dressed, making it messy and bland. I had the gnocci with meat sauce. The meat sauce was delicious, but the gnocchi size was inconsistent, leaving some very doughy, while others were perfect. My husband had the vegetable lasagna. Again, the veggies were barely cooked. Didn't love it. The service was good as well as the price point. The atmosphere was lively. And the attached bar looked like a cool place to have a drink.
